The paper discusses a game-theoretic model of price-setting on a network, which falls under the category of algorithmic game theory (cs.GT). The paper also discusses the impact of network structure on profits and social welfare, which is related to social network analysis (cs.SI). The paper also introduces a new measure of network centrality, which is related to machine learning (cs.LG) and econometrics (cs.EC). Finally, the paper discusses policy implications such as mergers and trade tariffs, which is related to network economics (cs.NI).
